FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - ERITREA
******************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Disease report, human & animal - East Africa 980207111506
Date: Fri, 13 Feb 1998
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties Disease Information, 11(7), 13
Feb 1998

OIE has published the following information received from from Dr. Uqubeab
Ghebremicael, Head of the Veterinary Services Division, Animal Resources
Department, Asmara:
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 8 December 1997.
Estimated date of first infection: 20 November 1997.
Location No. of outbreaks
Shambuko area (200 km south-west of Asmara) 3
Asmara area 2
Description of affected population: the outbreaks in Shambuko area affected
local zebu cattle, while those around Asmara were in dairy cattle (Holstein
Friesian crosses).
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
150,000 70 to 80% --- --- --
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Pirbright Laboratory, United
Kingdom (OIE World Reference Laboratory for foot and mouth disease).
B. Diagnostic tests used: serological; virus isolation in progress.
C. Causal agent: virus types A (five samples out of seven) and SAT 2 (two
samples out of seven).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: the disease is suspected to have
originated from a neighboring country.
B. Mode of spread: livestock movement both for trade and for grazing
(pastoral).
C. Other epidemiological details: although foot and mouth disease is
enzootic in Eritrea, only type O had been diagnosed in the past. Type SAT 2
in particular was considered exotic.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine and movement control
inside the country; vaccine has been ordered for a vaccination campaign.
--
